Here are the MSTest patterns for each scenario:

### 1. Windows-only tests — `[OSCondition]` (MSTest 3.10+)
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
public void WindowsRegistry_ReadsExpectedValue()
{
    var value = Registry.GetValue(@"HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\MyApp", "Setting", null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(value);
}
```

### 2. Skip in CI — `[CICondition]` (MSTest 3.10+)
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]
public void GpuRendering_ProducesExpectedOutput()
{
    var result = GpuRenderer.Render(scene);
    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
}
```

### 3. Flaky external API — `[Retry]` (MSTest 3.9+)
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)]
[Timeout(10000)]
public async Task WeatherApi_ReturnsForecast()
{
    var forecast = await _weatherClient.GetForecastAsync(_testContext.CancellationToken);
    Assert.IsNotNull(forecast);
}
```
Use `[Retry]` only for genuinely flaky external dependencies — not to mask race conditions or shared-state bugs.

### 4. Cleanup even on failure — `[TestCleanup]` or `IDisposable`
```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class TempFileTests : IDisposable
{
    private readonly string _tempFile;

    public TempFileTests()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void WriteAndRead_RoundTrips()
    {
        File.WriteAllText(_tempFile, "hello");
        Assert.AreEqual("hello", File.ReadAllText(_tempFile));
    }

    // Runs even if the test fails
    public void Dispose()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

You can also use `[TestCleanup]` instead of `IDisposable` — both run after every test regardless of pass/fail. The execution order is: `[TestCleanup]` → `DisposeAsync` → `Dispose`.
